commit_message:
Add support for Samples coming from Ceilometer

Can add or list Samples only. Samples are a sub-resource under a
Metric. Query-String filtering of samples is supported. The common
Resource type is changed to allow aliasing of resource attribute
names, required because Sample has two published and supported
resource formats within a single API version.

Change-Id: Ia1f157bffcd74dde203488917f2d5fa1df7e44aa

commit_message:
Fix the v2 auth plugin to handle empty token

The v3 plugin handles an empty token value, but the v2 plugin
would attempt to authenticate with a token of ''.  This change
should fix that.

Change-Id: Ia86377e7450a972bcb50303afeefacd9dc6426a9

Before this change, if /etc/neutron/rootwrap.d existed already and
was a dir or a link to a dir, an additional symlink, named rootwrap.d
was created within the rootwrap.d dir, eventually causing the
neutron-rootwrap command to fail and exit with non-zero.

Change-Id: I2f11d7e93ef1445afd1a58e4dd110f7369ec93ab
'}]
commit_message:
Ensure neutron rootwrap.d symlink is not nested

Before this change, if /etc/neutron/rootwrap.d existed already and
was a dir or a link to a dir, an additional symlink, named rootwrap.d
was created within the rootwrap.d dir, eventually causing the
neutron-rootwrap command to fail and exit with non-zero.

Change-Id: I2f11d7e93ef1445afd1a58e4dd110f7369ec93ab

[{'created': '2014-10-15 17:37:56.000000000', 'message': 'XenAPI: Add exit point after JEOS installation

If the user only want to run the installation of Ubuntu - to export the
template as an xva, it just needs to specify a non-empty value for:

EXIT_AFTER_JEOS_INSTALLATION

Change-Id: I558e2f2b18ee23c15c7e46e2f7e74543cf26b750
'}]
commit_message:
XenAPI: Add exit point after JEOS installation

If the user only want to run the installation of Ubuntu - to export the
template as an xva, it just needs to specify a non-empty value for:

EXIT_AFTER_JEOS_INSTALLATION

And the script will exit after the jeos template has been created.

Change-Id: I558e2f2b18ee23c15c7e46e2f7e74543cf26b750

In previous versions of the documentation, we tell the user
to both start, and enable, the messagebus/dbus service. This
is one and the same thing, and is installed and enabled by
default via a static systemd entry. We do not need to modify this.

bug should be considered soft as it would only throw an error on

commit_message:
Removes the requirement for messagebus configuration

In previous versions of the documentation, we tell the user
to both start, and enable, the messagebus/dbus service. This
is one and the same thing, and is installed and enabled by
default via a static systemd entry. We do not need to modify this.

This bug was originally reported against stable/icehouse but that
bug should be considered soft as it would only throw an error on
EL7 based platforms; this error can be ignored as it's harmless.

Change-Id: Id68d315efa7d563bf18d804d39ceb6892df95a58
Closes-Bug: #1358828

commit_message:
Nova has an undeclared dependency on python-cinderclient

Nova imports python-cinderclinet, which is not present by just
installing python-nova-api.  Hard yum-install it until upstream
fixes packaging.

Change-Id: I16b7caf2f3385637eaa2e73f83424109095262a5

commit_message:
Update endpoint when endpoint for one service type exists

create_endpoint will not work when deploy openstack once again
in same node if some attribute changes. we should update the
related endpoint in this case.

Closes-Bug: #1380460

commit_message:
Make nova-controller/*/start.sh and nova-controller/*/nova.conf +x

Make the start.sh and nova.conf files executable so they will run in the
container.  Without +x, the container exits immediately with a permission
error.

Change-Id: I111aa3f2dada241732cc113bedb09f38d96d012b

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary nova-controller which has no associated binary

There is not a nova-controller binary.  As a result, we don't really
need this container so remove it.  This container is stopping kolla
from starting the nova-controller pod.

Change-Id: Ic6d679c98b635e7e7c8b4b200e988ef8cb6d7ed6

commit_message:
Adds resource type classes

A set of resource types is added in /nova/resources/types.py. Simple
integer-based resources like CPU, RAM, and LocalDisk are included, in
addition to complex resources like NUMATopology, which uses the
primitives in nova.virt.hardware in order to update usage amounts and
calculate whether a requested NUMATopology for a to-be-launched instance
would fit in the NUMA cells advertised and used on a compute node.

A base nova.resources.types.ResourceType class is used as a generic
class interface for any resource, simple or complex, to create
nova.resources.amounts.AmountSpec and UsageSpec objects that can be used
to represent concrete amount and usage records. The idea here is to have
a single way of modeling some resource that is provided by a compute
node, and a single way of comparing a requested amount of something with
the capacity and usage records of the provider of that resource.

The next patch in the series adds methods to nova.objects.ComputeNode
that allow its resources (RAM, CPU, LocalDisk, PCI devices, NUMA cells,
etc) to be queried as nova.resource.amounts.UsageSpec objects.

Change-Id: I1962469d4d39c7ca2e9632ff8dad1e7f4de9125c
Partially-implements: resource-objects

[{'created': '2014-10-10 18:16:01.000000000', 'message': 'Add object models for comparing resource amounts

Right now, we have 4 distinct ways (!) of comparing resources in the
resource tracker:

- Straight integer amounts stored in top-level key/value pairs in the
  nova.compute.resource_tracker.ResourceTracker.old_resources dictionary
  attribute. For example: {"local_gb": X, "local_gb_used": Y}

- NUMA topology amounts and usages are stored as a serialized
  nova.virt.hardware.VirtNUMAInstanceTopology/VirtNUMAHostTopology
  pair in the old_resources dictionary under the 'numa_topology' key:
  {"numa_topology": JSON-BLOB}

- PCI device amounts and usages are separately tracked by the
  nova.compute.resource_tracker.ResourceTracker.pci_tracker object. This
  really is quite silly, and duplicates a ton of comparison functionality
  from both NUMA and the standard integer amount/usage stuff. The results
  of this pci_tracker work is placed into the "pci_devices" and
  "pci_passthrough_devices" (no idea why it was necessary to have two keys
  here...) as a JSON-serialized BLOB of information that comes directly from
  the pci_stats field in the compute_nodes table.

- The "extensible resource tracker" places "stuff" into a "stats" key in
  the top-level old_resources dictionary attribute. The "stuff" is a
  collection of free-form, unstructured, and undocumented amount
  information for whatever resource classes happen to be included by the
  deployer.

Just like we have 4 distinct ways of comparing resource amounts, we have
four totally different ways of comparing capacity of a resource with the
used amount of that resource:

- Straight integer amounts are compared using a simple `(total - used) >
  requested` formula.

- NUMA topology usage records use a set of classes that derive from
  nova.virt.hardware.VirtNUMATopology that enable different usage and cell
  topologies to be compared for fit. Unfortunately, the
  VirtNUMAHostTopology object inherited the nova.compute.claim.Claim
  object's claim_test() method, which tightly couples the (supposedly
  non-coupled) nova.virt.hardware classes to the Claim interface in the
  resource tracker.

- PCI device resource usages are managed in yet another completely
  different way, using the code in nova.pci.pci_manager.PciManager, which
  is a member of the resource tracker's pci_tracker attribute.

- And still yet the extensible resource tracker plugins offer another way
  of calculating and storing usage records: in a JSON blob that is passed
  from one plugin to another, which the plugin expected to update the
  supplied dictionary with a usage record that only it understands.

This patch adds the basic object models that will enable us to have a
single interface for comparing resource amounts and usages. It adds some
helper classes in /nova/resources/amounts.py that allow any "amount" of
a resource to be specified using the same generalized class, and any
capacity/usage of any resource to be both updated and check for
available room for a requested amount of some resource -- again, all in
a consistent generalized class interface.

The next patch in the series adds the actual resource types that
utilize the AmountSpec and UsageSpec objects introduced in this patch.

Change-Id: I6676fe3a9fb7d23adae1819cebab3a8cbad7487e
Partially-implements: resource-objects

commit_message:
Add object models for comparing resource amounts

Right now, we have 4 distinct ways (!) of comparing resources in the
resource tracker:

- Straight integer amounts stored in top-level key/value pairs in the
  nova.compute.resource_tracker.ResourceTracker.old_resources dictionary
  attribute. For example: {"local_gb": X, "local_gb_used": Y}

- NUMA topology amounts and usages are stored as a serialized
  nova.virt.hardware.VirtNUMAInstanceTopology/VirtNUMAHostTopology
  pair in the old_resources dictionary under the 'numa_topology' key:
  {"numa_topology": JSON-BLOB}

- PCI device amounts and usages are separately tracked by the
  nova.compute.resource_tracker.ResourceTracker.pci_tracker object. This
  really is quite silly, and duplicates a ton of comparison functionality
  from both NUMA and the standard integer amount/usage stuff. The results
  of this pci_tracker work is placed into the "pci_devices" and
  "pci_passthrough_devices" (no idea why it was necessary to have two keys
  here...) as a JSON-serialized BLOB of information that comes directly from
  the pci_stats field in the compute_nodes table.

- The "extensible resource tracker" places "stuff" into a "stats" key in
  the top-level old_resources dictionary attribute. The "stuff" is a
  collection of free-form, unstructured, and undocumented amount
  information for whatever resource classes happen to be included by the
  deployer.

Just like we have 4 distinct ways of comparing resource amounts, we have
four totally different ways of comparing capacity of a resource with the
used amount of that resource:

- Straight integer amounts are compared using a simple `(total - used) >
  requested` formula.

- NUMA topology usage records use a set of classes that derive from
  nova.virt.hardware.VirtNUMATopology that enable different usage and cell
  topologies to be compared for fit. Unfortunately, the
  VirtNUMAHostTopology object inherited the nova.compute.claim.Claim
  object's claim_test() method, which tightly couples the (supposedly
  non-coupled) nova.virt.hardware classes to the Claim interface in the
  resource tracker.

- PCI device resource usages are managed in yet another completely
  different way, using the code in nova.pci.pci_manager.PciManager, which
  is a member of the resource tracker's pci_tracker attribute.

- And still yet the extensible resource tracker plugins offer another way
  of calculating and storing usage records: in a JSON blob that is passed
  from one plugin to another, which the plugin expected to update the
  supplied dictionary with a usage record that only it understands.

This patch adds the basic object models that will enable us to have a
single interface for comparing resource amounts and usages. It adds some
helper classes in /nova/resources/amounts.py that allow any "amount" of
a resource to be specified using the same generalized class, and any
capacity/usage of any resource to be both updated and check for
available room for a requested amount of some resource -- again, all in
a consistent generalized class interface.

The next patch in the series adds the actual resource types that
utilize the AmountSpec and UsageSpec objects introduced in this patch.

Change-Id: I6676fe3a9fb7d23adae1819cebab3a8cbad7487e
Partially-implements: resource-objects

commit_message:
Fix the query to get all the AlarmStateHistory objects

It was using Alarm Definition Ids as Alarm Ids

Also, changed it to query Alarmed Metrics to match the given
dimensions instead of the Metric Definitions from the Alarm
Definition Expression. That allows you to get the alarms for a
specific host

Change-Id: I583b8ee017cad032a790de8861fffda07fdcc297

commit_message:
Remove DVR fips race condition

multiple threads making changes to DVR fips namespace and
data elements at the same time can encounter race
conditions and cause failures.
This fix serializes access to floatingip namespace
so that such race conditions do not occur.

Closes-bug: #1373100
Co-Authored-By: Carl Baldwin <carl.baldwin@hp.com>

Change-Id: Iad604c234c514238ebc9faee33c38d54358d2cc8

[{'created': '2014-10-13 17:26:32.000000000', 'message': "Add admin_net setting to nailgun-agent config

If a node has an admin IP address that is not the same subnet
as the Fuel master the nailgun-agent will fail to properly update
the node's IP after deployment. This leaves an invalid IP address in
the database which OSTF uses to connect to nodes and will cause
spurious test failures.

Change-Id: Ia623f9a038e994ccd65c036cc5a6eb1cdcd4551d
"}]
commit_message:
Add admin_net setting to nailgun-agent config

If a node has an admin IP address that is not the same subnet
as the Fuel master the nailgun-agent will fail to properly update
the node's IP after deployment. This leaves an invalid IP address in
the database which OSTF uses to connect to nodes and will cause
spurious test failures.

Change-Id: Ia623f9a038e994ccd65c036cc5a6eb1cdcd4551d

commit_message:
Refactor Heat dependencies for nova compute

Allows heat to have more control of the parallelism of the deploy
and allow easy integration of the new heat dependencies required for
nova compute integration. At present is difficult understand and has
unnecessary complex dependencies.

Change-Id: Ie566b8b14cbd98fe29cc2368a96d45cc74ca4715
Co-Authored-By: Nicholas Randon <nicholas.randon@hp.com>

Extract tripleo jobs to templates

Create new templates check-tripleo-jobs and
experimental-triple-jobs and use them everywhere.

Patch ported over from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/84026, rebased
and enhanced.

Co-Authored-By: Sergey Lukjanov <slukjanov@mirantis.com>

[{'created': '2014-10-15 17:38:26.000000000', 'message': 'XenAPI: Fix vimrc

DevStack installs a default minimal .vimrc file for the stack user.
Unfortunately the `syntax on` config line is not recognised by the vim
installed in DomU. It results in an annoying message being displayed

Change-Id: I224465cc3cdba3464ea0a9a751f250ecb6ddc9f3
'}]
commit_message:
XenAPI: Fix vimrc

DevStack installs a default minimal .vimrc file for the stack user.
Unfortunately the `syntax on` config line is not recognised by the vim
installed in DomU. It results in an annoying message being displayed
whenever the user is using vi. To avoid this issue, removing the `syntax
on` line.

Change-Id: I224465cc3cdba3464ea0a9a751f250ecb6ddc9f3

commit_message:
Carry deploy_keys_ref in triggers

Trigger was failing on private repos because it
wasn't including the deploy_keys_ref when calling
_build_artifact. This patch adds the reference back.

Change-Id: If17fde8e506f3ec0980451a5bc2bab28ee14fc3a

[{'created': '2014-10-16 13:00:09.000000000', 'message': "Update WSGI app creation to be compatible with Django 1.7

This resolves the following error when trying to run Horizon:

AppRegistryNotReady: The translation infrastructure cannot be
initialized before the apps registry is ready. Check that you don't
make non-lazy gettext calls at import time.

and is backwards-compatible with our currently supported versions (back
to 1.4).

Change-Id: I1e59f2bf6633a34cfe9230aa028f345e5fa70f94
Closes-Bug: #1382023
"}]
commit_message:
Update WSGI app creation to be compatible with Django 1.7

This resolves the following error when trying to run Horizon:

AppRegistryNotReady: The translation infrastructure cannot be
initialized before the apps registry is ready. Check that you don't
make non-lazy gettext calls at import time.

and is backwards-compatible with our currently supported versions (back
to 1.4).

Change-Id: I1e59f2bf6633a34cfe9230aa028f345e5fa70f94
Closes-Bug: #1382023

commit_message:
Fix doc build

Fix the following that shows up when running "python setup.py
build_sphinx":
manila/doc/source/adminref/index.rst:16:
WARNING: toctree contains reference to nonexisting document
u'adminref/launchpad'
manila/doc/source/adminref/index.rst:16:
WARNING: toctree contains reference to nonexisting document
u'adminref/gerrit'
manila/doc/source/adminref/index.rst:16:
WARNING: toctree contains reference to nonexisting document
u'adminref/jenkins'

checking consistency...
manila/doc/source/adminref/index.rst::
WARNING: document isn't included in any toctree

Cleanup adminref/index.rst file and remove content that is duplicated
from the devref/index.rst and not relevant here.

Change-Id: I57accea0f041ac59e507e4cf6461d2239f60b3b7

commit_message:
Minor: remove unnecessary intermediate variable

Removes an unnecessary intermediary variable and an
unnecessary list extend operation that implied previous
list members where there weren't any. There should be no
functional change. This just improves readability slightly.

Change-Id: Ice412c29be083d82e055cc0bc45ed8b97c7628d0

of the AlarmDefinition. Also has severity

The extra information is represented as an interior object in the

      "id": "52af7345-292d-4ac8-808b-249207fe91ab",

      "name": "high cpu and load"

Remove unused parameter to Alarm constructor

Change-Id: I32f7c2c780898541acf596e5c4c2b4f14824fb76
'}]
commit_message:
Add AlarmDefinition information to returned Alarm json

This is so the UI doesn't have to query again to get the name
of the AlarmDefinition. Also has severity

As soon as the CLI is changed, the alarm_definition_id field will be
removed from the alarm json. The id field inside the
alarm_definition object should be used instead

The extra information is represented as an interior object in the
json and looks like:

    "alarm_definition": {
      "severity": "LOW",
      "id": "52af7345-292d-4ac8-808b-249207fe91ab",
      "links": [
        {
          "href": "http://localhost:8080/alarm-definitions/52af7345-292d-4ac8-808b-249207fe91ab",
          "rel": "self"
        }
      ],
      "name": "high cpu and load"
    }

Implemented equals and hashcode for Alarm

Remove unused parameter to Alarm constructor

Change-Id: I32f7c2c780898541acf596e5c4c2b4f14824fb76

commit_message:
Fix bad header bug in glance-replicator

When trying to use "glance-replicator livecopy" to replicate the
images from one OpenStack glance to another, it encounters "Bad
header" error for "x-image-meta-virtual-size" header. This is
because this header is not in the whitelist of v1 API headers of
form "x-image-meta-xxx".

Another problem after adding this "x-image-meta-virtual-size" to
header whitelist is that the sqlalchemy fail due to virual_size is
"None", which cannot be converted to int. To fix this problem, we
should avoid converting the None value attribute in GET
/v1/images/detail response to the header of POST /v1/images. I
added the None value check, following what the way in
glance/common/utils.py image_meta_to_http_headers() method.

Closes-Bug: #1373333

Change-Id: I13182c4e3212024a9d5663cefd2951c576961f4f
(cherry picked from commit 4b2304d6bb1d77db1e411f375a00a93aaabca262)

'}]
commit_message:
Fix for adopt glance.store library in Glance

The store module is removed from glance project and new glance_store
module is created, but the glance project code was not updated
properly for the required changes.

_get_from_store and _get_size methods raises store.NotFound exception
from glance_store but not caught in the glance api.

Updated exception.NotFound to store.NotFound which returns 404 NotFound
response to the user.

Closes-Bug: #1380552
Change-Id: Ia947e33ae09b8625b3301dc98eca8049164228ba

commit_message:
Use specific exceptions instead of the general MetadefRecordNotFound

Currently, when metadef namespaces, objects or properties are not found
by ID, a general MetadefRecordNotFound exception is raised. Instead,
just use the specific MetadefNamespaceNotFound, MetadefObjectNotFound or
MetadefPropertyNotFound exceptions.

Conflicts:
        glance/db/sqlalchemy/metadef_api/namespace.py
        glance/db/sqlalchemy/metadef_api/object.py
        glance/db/sqlalchemy/metadef_api/property.py

Change-Id: Icb6bf543015305174720f2fd950f5e4984f39798
Closes-Bug: 1367650
(cherry picked from commit 86657d9a150ad5e0e5340c4657c0725bd6910e26)

commit_message:
NetApp fix for default host type in eseries

This fixes the issue where the default host type
provided in mapping should be high performing LnxALUA
type for eseries. It also makes it configurable in case
users want to configure a different host type.

Closes-Bug: #1365884

Change-Id: I30992ca69c25c3c02334470aae90c32731a5f3f4
(cherry picked from commit a120ede9ae3f18756db07d1d6696b9ac773b84bf)

commit_message:
Fix keystone_endpoint provider

Provider logic was broken for the new style keystone_endpoints
(the ones with "region/service" resource names). Due to this
puppet created new keystone endpoint even for existing ones on the
2nd+ runs.

We need to use common hash key for endpoint_hash in the provider
for both resource types ("region/service" and "service":region =>)
So we just force endpoint_hash to use "region/service" as hash key
for any "keystone_endpoint" resource type.

This patch and the problem will go away after we sync keystone
module with upstream.

Cherry-picked from: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/128384/
Change-Id: I9eaaaf0f63db36a9837cc2141c293efd8adfd68e
Closes-bug: 1375254

commit_message:
Improved templates_names method in fuel_agent

This change is to make it possible to find templates for
both underline separated and dash separated profiles.
1) ubuntu_1204_x86_64
2) centos-65_x86_64

Change-Id: I5f730b35be67de83338fa3fc34df315929da49df
Implements: blueprint image-based-provisioning

I dont think this change is going to solve the problem, I have encountered similar issues while rebooting my undercloud, br-ctlplane would come up without the physical interface association,
to solve this I took the recommendation from opevswitch community 

Ideally we shouldnt auto start the ovs-bridge and ports, rather we should let the openvswitch to start them, I'd suggest to modify the network/interfaces file to match this recommendation
https://github.com/emaste/openvswitch/blob/master/debian/openvswitch-switch.README.Debian  and do your reboot test

After commenting out the $auto bridge $auto interface lines, I was able to reboot successfully, the bridge came up with no issues."}, {'account_id': 5209, 'date': '2014-09-29 22:38:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
ensure that port is added to bridge after a reboot

This is a change to the interfaces file to allow
openvswitch to start the ovs-bridge and to add the
specified ports.  Without this change, the bridge
comes up after a reboot of the seed or undercloud,
but the port associated with the physical interface
doesn't come up.

Change-Id: Ic968f39b16934c9e55d9aa448cbd9de54f659d4d
Closes-Bug: 1373063
Co-Authored-By: Ashok kumaran B<ashokkumaran.b@hp.com>

commit_message:
Change owner/group of all files in /var/log/keystone after initializing PKI

Because the log file for keystone is keystone-all.log on openSUSE we should
not use the filename to be distribution independent.

Change-Id: I2eb2735edc61b81299004109db0304fae8417197

The Neutron Hyper-V agent fails occasionally with a x_wmi_uninitialised_thread

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V COM initializazion race condition

The Neutron Hyper-V agent fails occasionally with a x_wmi_uninitialised_thread
exception due to lack of initialization of the COM library.

Since it's not possible to know in advance which thread is assigned to the functions
performing COM calls, this patch adds a decorator to each relevant public method
in any Hyper-V *utils module, wrapping calls in CoInitializeEx / ConUninitialize pairs.

For details:
http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/ms695279(v=vs.85).aspx

Change-Id: Ica20db6dbc1ad7a42c19d4502f714499b1c8d4ef
Closes-Bug: #1298034

commit_message:
Cleanup branding and requirements

Remove docutils pin, it's not needed anymore.
Remove oslosphinx import, it's not needed for a stackforge project.
Use normal branding, a stackforge project cannot use the OpenStack
themes.
Update requirements.txt from global requirements.

Change-Id: I0eaecf825272668c16be6cadd917c9b782a8c3a7

commit_message:
Move subsections inside the section

When I updated the VMAX Cinder driver doc, I put subsections
outside of the section that referenced them. The published doc
doesn't look right. This patch is to move subsections inside
the section.

Here is how the VMAX doc looks like currently:

http://docs.openstack.org/trunk/config-reference/content/emc-vmax-driver.html

The following links are displayed at the top of the doc:

System requirements
Supported operations
Install the python-pywbem package
Set up SMI-S
cinder.conf configuration file
cinder_emc_config_CONF_GROUP_ISCSI.xml configuration file
FC Zoning with VMAX
iSCSI with VMAX
Set up the VMAX drivers
VMAX masking view and group naming info
Concatenated or striped volumes

As shown above, links to the sub-sections inside the "Set up the VMAX
drivers" section also showed up in the beginning.

The purpose of this patch is to hide the sub-sections inside the
"Set up the VMAX drivers" section, so that only the following links
showing up in the beginning of the doc:

System requirements
Supported operations
Set up the VMAX drivers
VMAX masking view and group naming info
Concatenated or striped volumes

Change-Id: I952386116f696c59412291d1f89afd7f9220d678

[{'created': '2014-10-14 13:00:34.000000000', 'message': 'Fix libvirt watchdog support

Using the flavor extra_specs property "hw_watchdog_action" was broken.
Scheduling of a new instance always failed with NoValidHostFound error
because of ComputeCapabilitiesFilter, which treated this property as a
host capability to be checked.

Commit f0ff4d51057080e769407e873e5ed212f15b773d caused the problem.

To fix this watchdog_action property is put into 'hw:' scope, so
that it will be ignored by ComputeCapabilitiesFilter in scheduler and
handled in libvirt driver. The doc must be fixed accordingly.

Now driver accepts both 'hw_watchdog_action' and
'hw:watchdog_action', tests were edited for these cases.
Were added TODO items to delete the compat code in the next release.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1367344

commit_message:
Fix libvirt watchdog support

Using the flavor extra_specs property "hw_watchdog_action" was broken.
Scheduling of a new instance always failed with NoValidHostFound error
because of ComputeCapabilitiesFilter, which treated this property as a
host capability to be checked.

Commit f0ff4d51057080e769407e873e5ed212f15b773d caused the problem.

To fix this watchdog_action property is put into 'hw:' scope, so
that it will be ignored by ComputeCapabilitiesFilter in scheduler and
handled in libvirt driver. The doc must be fixed accordingly.

Now driver accepts both 'hw_watchdog_action' and
'hw:watchdog_action', tests were edited for these cases.
Were added TODO items to delete the compat code in the next release.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1367344

Change-Id: Ic5344ec34a130ee5a0ed2c7348af0b9d79e3508e

commit_message:
NetApp fix to set non default server port in api

The non default netapp_server_port config option was not
getting set in api even if specified in cinder.conf. Its
made non mandatory and set if specified in the configuration.

Change-Id: I62943427e0caac2742cce4ce56c1a49917f9210d
Closes-bug: #1322379

commit_message:
Update the puppet coding style

Disable check in rakefile:
* disable 80 chars
* disable variable scope
* disable class inherits from params class
* disable class parameter defaults
The remaining work is in the correction puppet code specifications

Change-Id: I4448f1776ca3c7c3ea4a3bb64672785a62572663
Closes-Bug: #1338228

commit_message:
add script to generate test event data

similar to make_test_data.py, this script generates a set of events
and writes them to the database (defined in ceilometer.conf).

configurable options:
- start - number of days in past to start test data
- end - number of days into the future to start test data
- interval - period between events, in minutes
- event_types - number of unique event_types

Change-Id: I80e023a82f7d5129649a5b1de5256e41e901e3c1

commit_message:
postgresql: use postgres db instead of template1

In PostgreSQL template1 database is kind of special, as all new databases are
copied from it, when you do CREATE DATABASE. This implies a few restrictions:
e.g. you can't have more than one active session to template1, if one of them
tries to create a database. It will fail with:

    ERROR: source database "template1" is being accessed by other users

Using of postgres database instead of template1 resolves this issue.

Closes-Bug: #1355929

Change-Id: I8b1a36163984fbef6be66964456072d32da6a9d0
(cherry picked from commit 02fa15b4caaa414930b6ddf6a3a9fe8019751c26)

Provider logic was broken for the new style keystone_endpoints
(the ones with "region/service" resource names). Due to this
puppet created new keystone endpoint even for existing ones on the
2nd+ runs.

We need to use common hash key for endpoint_hash in the provider
for both resource types ("region/service" and "service":region =>)
So we just force endpoint_hash to use "region/service" as hash key
for any "keystone_endpoint" resource type.

Closes-bug: 1375254

commit_message:
Fix keystone_endpoint provider

Provider logic was broken for the new style keystone_endpoints
(the ones with "region/service" resource names). Due to this
puppet created new keystone endpoint even for existing ones on the
2nd+ runs.

We need to use common hash key for endpoint_hash in the provider
for both resource types ("region/service" and "service":region =>)
So we just force endpoint_hash to use "region/service" as hash key
for any "keystone_endpoint" resource type.

This patch and the problem will go away after we sync keystone
module with upstream.

Change-Id: I9eaaaf0f63db36a9837cc2141c293efd8adfd68e
Closes-bug: 1375254
